<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911106-0153</DOCNO><DOCID>911106-0153.</DOCID><HL>   Former Top Official   With Columbia Sandamp;L   Convicted in Scheme</HL><DATE>11/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   CSV TAXES</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)</IN><NS>TAXES (TAX)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Jeffrey S. Worthy, former Columbia Savingsandamp; Loan Association vice president and director of financialplanning, was convicted of engaging in a scheme to sell theBeverly Hills, Calif., thrift $166 million in fraudulent&quot;leveraged lease packages&quot; from 1983 to 1987.   Mr. Worthy, the U.S. attorney's office here said, pleadedguilty to participating in criminal activity between April10, 1985, and November 1987. During that time, Mr. Worthyreceived about $1.4 million in kickbacks from Parker NorthAmerican Corp. in exchange for his assistance in reviewingand recommending that Columbia buy the lease packages, theoffice said.</LP><TEXT>   The packages supposedly included equipment that Parker hadleased to banks and thrifts, but many of them were based onequipment and leases that didn't exist, U.S. investigatorshave said. The kickbacks, the U.S. attorney's office said,were about one percent of the total purchase price of thelease packages.   Columbia was seized by federal regulators earlier thisyear after failing to sell off its badly devalued junk-bondportfolio.   Mr. Worthy, who left Columbia in 1988, was also convictedof tax evasion for not reporting on income tax returns for a&quot;substantial amount&quot; of the money he received as kickbacks.He pleaded guilty to evading payment of about $123,000 intaxes in 1985. Mr. Worthy faces a maximum sentence of 25years in prison, restitution of the $1.4 million, a $500,000fine, and a mandatory special assessment of $100.   Brian W. Fink, a former Parker vice president, has pleadedguilty to conspiracy and tax evasion in the scheme. AndMichael E. Parker has been charged in a federal grand juryindictment with racketeering, money laundering, payment andreceipt of kickbacks, bank fraud and tax evasion inconnection with the alleged scheme. His trial is set for Jan.9.   Mr. Parker, former chairman of Parker Automotive Corp.,Costa Mesa, Calif., which makes fuel-system flushingproducts, also sold the lease packages as tax shelters toColumbia through Parker North American, according to U.S.attorneys.</TEXT></DOC>